{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538323"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16163"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16163"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.3,0.04,0.03,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105396"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8854"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87823"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3160"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105396"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by her housemate who is concerned about her unusual behaviour over the past two weeks. The patient has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is in her final year of university studies. When asked about her symptoms, she responds: \u0022The clouds are moving fast today... my mother always liked blue... blue whales are endangered... I need to save the oceans... the government is poisoning the water... my teeth feel like metal.\u0022 She has not slept well for several nights.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears agitated but is not aggressive. Her pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. She is oriented to person but not to place or time. Physical examination reveals no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s thought pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tangentiality","Flight of ideas","Word salad","Circumstantiality","Loosening of associations"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates classic features of formal thought disorder, specifically \u003Cstrong\u003Eloosening of associations\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as derailment). The patient\u0027s speech shows a pattern where ideas shift between topics beyond what would be considered \u0027normal\u0027; in this case, they have no meaningful or logical connection. While each phrase is comprehensible in isolation, the connections between thoughts are tenuous or absent (clouds \u2192 mother \u2192 whales \u2192 oceans \u2192 government \u2192 teeth).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlight of ideas\u003C/strong\u003E differs in that while thoughts change rapidly, there are usually identifiable connections between ideas (often rhyming, word plays, or semantic associations), and it typically occurs in the context of mania with pressured speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETangentiality\u003C/strong\u003E refers to replies to questions that are obliquely related or completely unrelated to the question asked, but the speech itself maintains internal coherence. This patient\u0027s speech pattern shows disruption of coherence between successive thoughts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECircumstantiality\u003C/strong\u003E involves providing excessive, unnecessary detail before eventually reaching the point. While the path to the answer is indirect, there is eventually a return to the original topic, which is not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWord salad\u003C/strong\u003E represents a more severe form of thought disorder where speech becomes completely incoherent and grammatically incorrect. In this case, while the connections between ideas are loose, each individual phrase remains grammatically intact and comprehensible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of formal thought disorder, particularly in a young adult with no psychiatric history, should prompt consideration of both primary psychotic disorders (such as schizophrenia) and secondary causes (such as substance use, autoimmune encephalitis, or other organic brain pathology). A thorough medical workup would be indicated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Loosening of associations is characterized by speech that shifts between topics in a way that lacks logical connection","Formal thought disorder is distinct from cognitive impairment or confusion","New onset psychotic symptoms warrant thorough medical evaluation to exclude organic causes"],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87823"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16163"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87823"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-08T22:32:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-08T22:32:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8854"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105396"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/188"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Psychotic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T14:32:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}}